<sup>a</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Gorman%20PN"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id6"><span class="name western">Paul N Gorman</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id6">
<h3><span class="name western">Paul N Gorman</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a)</sup>Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Department of Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology, 3181 S.W. Sam Jackson Park Rd., Portland, Oregon 97239-3098</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>d)</sup>Oregon Health &amp; Science University Hospital, 3181 S.W. Sam Jackson Park Rd., Portland, Oregon 97239-3098</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Gorman%20PN"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Paul N Gorman</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a,</sup><sup>d</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>a)</sup>Oregon Health &amp; Science University, Department of Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology, 3181 S.W. Sam Jackson Park Rd., Portland, Oregon 97239-3098</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>b)</sup>Cambia Health Solutions, 100 SW Market St., Portland, OR 97201</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>c)</sup>University of Wisconsin - Madison, School of Nursing, 701 Highland Avenue, Madison, WI 53705</div>
<div id="A4">
<sup>d)</sup>Oregon Health &amp; Science University Hospital, 3181 S.W. Sam Jackson Park Rd., Portland, Oregon 97239-3098</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline">Corresponding Author: Dana Womack, PhD, RN, Assistant Professor, Department of Medical Informatics &amp; Clinical Epidemiology, Oregon Health &amp; Science University, 3181 S.W. Sam Jackson Park Rd., Portland, Oregon 97239, United States, <span>womacda@ohsu.edu</span> (Dana Womack), Mobile phone: 703-728-2593</p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2019 Nov.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC6834115  NIHMSID: NIHMS1041589  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31422247/" class="usa-link">31422247</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.apergo.2019.102893" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Appl Ergon</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p id="P1">Through everyday care experiences, nurses develop expertise in recognition of capacity strain in hospital workplaces. Through qualitative interview, experienced nurses identify common activity changes and adaptive work strategies that may signal an imbalance between patient demand and service supply at the bedside. Activity change examples include nurse helping behaviors across patient assignments, increased volume of nurse calls from patient rooms, and decreased presence of staff at the nurses’ station. Adaptive work strategies encompass actions taken to recruit resources, move work in time, reduce work demands, or reduce thoroughness of task performance. Nurses’ knowledge of perceptible signs of strain provides a foundation for future exploration and development of real-time indicators of capacity strain in hospital-based work systems.</p>
<section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> Socio-technical systems, Capacity Strain, Nursing, Workload, Strategies</p></section></section><section id="S1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. Introduction</h2>
<p id="P2">Hospital-based Registered Nurses (RNs) regularly navigate ever-changing patient needs in everyday clinical care. Flexible adaptation to the demands of dynamically changing situations is an essential nursing skill, but nurses experience strain when it becomes challenging or impossible to complete required tasks given available resources and time. Different terms are used to describe multiple aspects of this phenomenon, including elevated workload, workplace stress, clinician overload, fatigue, understaffed shifts and capacity strain. For purposes of this study, we use the term capacity strain, defined as a state of varying duration in which aggregate patient need (service demand) exceeds available nursing resources, physical, temporal, and/or cognitive (service supply) in hospital work systems. This definition is adapted from previously published definitions of capacity strain (<a href="#R4" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R4">Bagshaw et al., 2017</a>, <a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">Halpern, 2011</a>). Many studies have been conducted to establish relationships between resource availability, workload and nurse performance. Capacity strain can negatively influence a unit’s ability to provide high-quality care (<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">Baethge et al., 2016</a>, <a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">Halpern, 2011</a>), and can contribute to reduced ability to detect and correct system failures (<a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">Gaffney, 2016</a>). Competing workplace demand experienced as interruptions can negatively affect completion of patient care tasks (<a href="#R35" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R35">Sasangohar et al., 2017</a>). Understaffed shifts are associated with negative patient outcomes including increased mortality (<a href="#R29" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R29">Needleman et al., 2011</a>) and missed nursing care (<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">Cho, 2015</a>, <a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">Kalisch et al., 2011</a>).</p>
<p id="P3">Dynamic adaptation enables employees to sustain target performance across a variety of workplace conditions (<a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">Wears, 2015</a>). However, when the force of a disturbance or growing demand overwhelms the adaptive capacity of employees providing a service, decompensation, or a loss of target performance, can occur (<a href="#R39" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R39">Woods and Branlat, 2011</a>). Although signs of nurse adaptation may precede negative nurse or patient outcomes, hospital metrics are not currently designed to detect dynamic emergence of capacity strain or signs of adaptive work performance on patient care units. For example, nursing hours per patient day is a whole-day metric that lacks the temporal resolution required to detect fluctuations in patient demand across a 24-hour period (<a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">Hall et al., 2006</a>, <a href="#R28" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R28">Min and Scott, 2016</a>). Similarly, the average circumstances assumed by patient-to-nurse ratios may not reflect current reality in dynamic work settings (<a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">Lineweaver, 2014</a>). Patient classification systems inform shift-level staffing decisions through estimation of patient-level workload (<a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">Malloch, 2015</a>) but classification systems are not designed to detect performance obstacles (<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">Carayon and Gurses, 2005</a>), unexpected events or interruptions due to the dynamic nature of these events (<a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">Fasoli and Haddock, 2010</a>, <a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">Malloch, 2015</a>).</p>
<p id="P4">Through everyday care experiences, frontline RNs and charge nurses become experts in recognition of workplace cues that suggest nurses are adapting to a disturbance or growing strain, yet documentation of nurses’ heuristic knowledge of subtle signs of strain is a gap in current literature. This paper addresses this gap by describing workplace characteristics, activity changes, and RN behaviors that are recognized by frontline RNs as signs of capacity strain at the bedside. The focus of this study is identification of workplace cues to which nurses regularly attend to maintain awareness of capacity strain in the hospital workplace. Changes in RN cognition that may contribute to signs of strain is beyond the scope of this study. An improved understanding of signs of capacity strain can help to guide improved monitoring, proactive intervention during times of strain, and ultimately the redesign of work systems to reduce capacity strain and improve the well-being and performance of nurses.</p></section><section id="S2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. Methods</h2>
<section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1. Design</h3>
<p id="P5">A qualitative descriptive design was selected to elicit experienced RNs’ knowledge of signs of capacity strain at the bedside. Data were collected through semi-structured focus group interviews. A qualitative approach offers the opportunity to gather rich data and build knowledge of workplace characteristics and activity patterns recognized by frontline nurses as signs of capacity strain.</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2. Participant selection and ethical considerations</h3>
<p id="P6">A purposive sample of experienced RNs was recruited from a single academic medical center. Inclusion criteria included a minimum of two years hospital work experience and current employment as a bedside RN on a medical-surgical or medical intensive care unit (MICU). This experience threshold matches typical minimum requirements for nursing certification in a specialized area of practice. Two units were selected to represent a range of RN work experiences and patient populations. Both units utilize a primary care model of nursing care delivery and share an H-shaped physical layout with patient rooms lining two outer hallways. Staff nurses on both units utilize an electronic health record (EHR) with electronic shift hand-off functionality. In addition to electronic tools, nurses utilize handwritten notes to track the status of outstanding care tasks. Dayshift RNs were recruited to foster rich dialogue between participants who share similar temporal rhythms in the workplace.</p>
<p id="P7">The study protocol was reviewed and approved by the Oregon Health &amp; Science Institutional Review Board. Participants were recruited via oral presentation, workplace flyers, and e-mail. All participants provided verbal consent to participate in an audio recorded focus group session. RNs were off-duty during data collection and were remunerated for 90 minutes commensurate with their regular hourly rate of pay.</p></section><section id="S5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3. Participant characteristics</h3>
<p id="P8">A total of 19 RNs participated in a 90-minute focus group session. Each session was comprised of 4 – 5 RNs representing 3 – 40 years of care delivery experience (<a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>). RN representation was roughly equal across the two study units. All participants reported working 12-hour work shifts, and 94% were female. Four focus groups were deemed sufficient given role-based homogeneity of participants and achievement of data saturation.</p>
