<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.4. Data collection</h3>
<p id="P9">An overview of the study, including risks and benefits of participation, was provided at the beginning of each focus group session and all participants provided verbal consent to participate. Focus group interviews were facilitated by study authors DW and NV. As an informative icebreaker activity, participants were invited to draw the workload trajectory of their last shift, utilizing proposed definitions of levels of capacity strain (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>) adapted from states of resilience (<a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">Hollnagel and Sundstrom, 2006</a>), efficiency-thoroughness principle (<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">Hollnagel, 2009</a>), and stress-strain plots (<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">Woods and Wreathall, 2008</a>).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T2"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 2:</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P61">Proposed definitions of levels of capacity strain</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
