</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Nominal</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Can meet workplace demand with available time and resources</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Slow</td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">More time/resources are available than are required</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P10">Semi-structured questions were used to guide focus group discussions. All sessions were audio recorded and transcribed. A note taker captured participant identifiers and a few spoken words with each speaker transition to facilitate participant attribution in written transcripts. The interview guide was piloted with seven 4th year nursing students prior to data collection. The pilot resulted in minor changes to the final interview guide (<a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>). Pilot data were not included in study analysis.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T3"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 3:</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P62">Semi-structured focus group interview guide</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1"><col align="left" valign="middle" span="1"></colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">We are interested in feedback regarding draft definitions of levels of capacity strain used in the “last shift trajectory” exercise.<ul id="L3" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P63">In what ways are proposed definitions consistent with your past work experiences?</p></li>
<li><p id="P64">What modifications might you suggest?</p></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">In your everyday clinical work experience:<ul id="L4" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P65">What are telltale signs of a good work shift? A bad shift?</p></li>
<li><p id="P66">Are there better or worse times of the day to fall behind? Why?</p></li>
<li><p id="P67">In what ways can workload fluctuation across a shift influence patient safety?</p></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Think back to a time when your capacity for care, or your ability to meet patient needs in a timely manner, was really stretched:<ul id="L5" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P68">What events contributed to the stretch?</p></li>
<li><p id="P69">How did you recognize that you were stretched?</p></li>
<li><p id="P70">In what ways did activity in the workplace change?</p></li>
<li><p id="P71">What work adjustments did you make to meet the demands of the situation?</p></li>
</ul>
</td></tr>
<tr><td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Are there other important aspects of capacity strain that you would like to discuss?</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.5. Focus group procedures</h3>
<p id="P11">An overview of the study, including risks and benefits, was provided at the beginning of each session. Participants provided verbal consent to participate in an audio-recorded focus group. Proposed definitions of levels of capacity strain (<a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>) were reviewed to establish a common understanding of terms and concepts, allow nurses to provide feedback on the definitions, and establish study scope. Participants were provided with examples of capacity strain, and were informed that capacity strain related to natural or man-made disasters is beyond the scope of the current study. Nurses drew the workload trajectory of their last shift using the proposed definitions of levels of capacity strain and added emoji stickers to represent their subjective work experience. RNs briefly shared the story of their last work shift as a transition from icebreaker activity to focus group discussion.</p>
<p id="P12">Participants were invited to respond to open ended questions from the interview guide. Initial questions focused on workload level definitions and temporal patterns in everyday clinical care. Participants were then invited to recall a period of time during a past work shift when they were “really stretched”. Subsequent questions focused on workplace characteristics, activity changes, and adaptive work strategies that emerged during times of strain.</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.6. Interpretation of data</h3>
<p id="P13">Focus group audio recordings were transcribed using Express Scribe software. A coding template was constructed through individual coding of the transcript from the first focus group session by authors DW, NV and LS, followed by consensus-building deliberation and template revision. The final coding template contained 9 themes (<a href="#T4" class="usa-link">Table 4</a>) and four categories. All focus group sessions were coded by DW in Quirkos® qualitative analysis software using the final coding template.</p>
