</ul></td>
</tr></tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T4/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section></section><section id="S9"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. Results</h2>
<p id="P14">Participant responses to semi-structured questions were largely consistent within and across focus group sessions. RN participants from the MICU provided examples of activity changes and adaptive responses to capacity strain that were very similar to examples provided by medical-surgical RN participants. All participants described similar work shift rhythms for the day shift on both patient care units.</p>
<section id="S10"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Last shift trajectory exercise and definitions of levels of capacity strain</h3>
<section id="S11"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1. Variable demand during last shift worked</h4>
<p id="P15">RN participants described a dynamic workplace in which capacity strain is variable across the minutes and hours of a work shift. Nearly all participant “last shift trajectory” artifacts spanned 2–4 capacity strain levels. “Nominal” and “Stretched” were the most frequently included workload levels across participants.</p>
<p id="P16">Emoji stickers were used to represent subjective work experience. Across all artifacts, emojis used in the lowest capacity strain level typically depicted joyful expressions, while emojis used in the highest capacity strain level reflected frustration, fatigue and displeasure.</p></section><section id="S12"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2. Definition of levels of capacity strain</h4>
<p id="P17">RNs in all focus groups expressed that proposed definitions of levels of capacity strain were understandable and represented familiar work states. RNs reported that many work shifts involve recurrent fluctuation between nominal and really stretched states. Several participants stated that they “always feel stretched”.</p>
<p id="P18">One nurse suggested addition of a level for life-threatening emergencies between “really stretched” and “calamity”. Another suggested striking the phrase “no reserve for emergencies” because code teams are nearly always available. Several nurses suggested that “prioritization of efficiency over thoroughness” is equally applicable to the “stretched” and “really stretched” levels, and remarked that the phrases “trade-off” and “prioritization of efficiency over thoroughness” are accurate and descriptive but may be unfamiliar to nurses.</p></section></section><section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Activity Patterns</h3>
<section id="S14"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.3. Temporal shift rhythms</h4>
<p id="P19">Day shift work rhythms described by RNs were largely shared across patient care units. RNs described an intense work period between 7:30 am and 11:00 am. One participant compared the start of dayshift to “Double Dutch” with many competing demands for time and attention layered atop time-sensitive shift routines such as 9:00 am medications, assessments, and clinical documentation. The 8:00 – 10:00 am time period was described as the worst time of day for unexpected events to occur “because we all know that if you get behind during the morning, you’re just scrambling for the rest of the day.”</p>
<p id="P20">Participants described four peak medication administration times per work shift that reflect medication policies established by the pharmacy department. Admissions typically begin late morning and continue throughout the shift. Brief lulls may occur around 11:00 am or 2:00 pm. The 11:00 am to 3:00 pm timeframe is characterized by patient discharges and rotating meal breaks.</p>
<p id="P21">A brief patient report is provided to a “lunch buddy” before RNs leave a unit for a meal break. Multiple RNs explained that they frequently receive calls about patients when off the unit, which may result in the need to abandon lunch. Nurses describe attempts to stagger their meal breaks but acknowledge that reduced staff during mealtime contributes to workplace strain.</p>
<p id="P22">RNs repeat assessments and modify nursing care plans in late afternoon. End-of-shift activities include making a record of patient intake &amp; output and hand-off documentation. Response to urgent situations, care coordination, implementation of new provider orders, patient rounding, patient mobility, turns, toileting, hygiene care, and many other care tasks occur repeatedly as needed during a work shift. Nurses noted that “falling behind” at 6:00 pm or later is impactful because handover report can be delayed, and it becomes difficult to leave work on time. Typical contributors to capacity strain at end of shift include change in patient condition, completion of clinical documentation, and late-shift admissions.</p></section><section id="S15"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.4. Signs of manageability</h4>
<p id="P23">Ability to address self-care needs including hydration, nutrition and restroom breaks was the most frequently reported sign of a “good shift”. Additional signs include timely clinical documentation and getting off work on time. RNs noted that clinical documentation time doubles as time for rehydration and foot rest. The atmosphere on a good shift is pleasant, with short social conversations (e.g. “How was your weekend?”) between care activities.</p></section><section id="S16"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.5. Demand bursts</h4>
<p id="P24">RNs report that workload can vary considerably across a shift. Workload escalation may occur as a result of a single large event, multiple small events, or a gradual increase in aggregate patient demand. Participants shared that “falling behind” is often preceded by a cluster of tasks that each require ≥15 minutes of uninterrupted time.</p>
<p id="P25">In multiple focus groups, nurses described maintaining a dynamically reprioritized mental list of outstanding tasks. RNs report rapid acceleration in work tempo as task backlogs increase in length. The term “running” was frequently used to describe periods of pressure that could last minutes to hours. RNs explained that demand bursts are followed by a recovery period in which the task backlog is cleared. One participant noted that recovery time may be longer than the initial demand burst.</p>
<p id="P26">Multiple RNs explained that they are regularly pulled in multiple directions at the same time and may need to pause current activity to attend to other emergent tasks. Demand bursts were described as particularly stressful when an RN is occupied in a task (e.g. sterile dressing change) that involves safety risk to patients if it is interrupted.</p></section><section id="S17"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.6. Perceptible signs of strain</h4>
<p id="P27">Across all focus groups, RNs described similar perceptible changes in the work environment that occur during times of strain (<a href="#T5" class="usa-link">Table 5</a>). Reported cues include an empty nurse station when staff are busy in patient rooms, and staff visibly “ping-ponging” between rooms due to frequent task switching. Response to call lights and phones are slowed, and RNs tend to be asked for help every time they sit down to chart, as nurses report that “sitting” is interpreted by others as “being available”.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T5"><h5 class="obj_head">Table 5:</h5>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P81">Activity changes that serve as perceptible signs of strain</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">RN assignment level</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Patient care unit level</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody><tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L9" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P82">RNs entering/exiting rooms of patients assigned to other RNs (assistance across patient assignments)</p></li>
<li><p id="P83">Elevated patient call light volume</p></li>
<li><p id="P84">Frequently repeated room checks</p></li>
<li><p id="P85">Multiple staff assisting a single patient</p></li>
<li><p id="P86">Specific medication combinations recognized to be associated with heavy patient workload</p></li>
<li><p id="P87">RNs in constant motion, limited time at computers</p></li>
</ul></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L10" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P88">No staff visible in the nurses’ station or hallways</p></li>
<li><p id="P89">Patients arriving and leaving the unit in close time proximity</p></li>
<li><p id="P90">RNs “ping-ponging” between rooms</p></li>
<li><p id="P91">Queuing of RNs at medication dispensing devices</p></li>
<li><p id="P92">Physical presence of code blue or rapid response teams</p></li>
<li><p id="P93">Absence of a unit clerk or nursing assistants</p></li>
<li><p id="P94">Perpetual patient call light and incoming phone call tones</p></li>
</ul></td>
</tr></tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P28">Several nurses noted that low census shifts are often more difficult than high census shifts because support staff roles (e.g. nursing assistant, clerk) may go unstaffed. During a demand burst, patients may receive assistance from another RN (e.g. charge nurse) who steps in to help.</p>
<p id="P29">Reported patient characteristics that are commonly present during times of strain include delirium, pain, incontinence, high psycho-social need, and low mobility. RNs noted that patient medication profiles also contain workload cues. For example, patients taking lactulose and rifaxamin in combination are likely to have a diagnosis of hepatic encephalopathy and may require heavy assistance related to severe illness, cognitive deficits, and frequent diarrhea.</p>
<p id="P30">In addition to perceptible signs of strain, RNs discussed internally perceived phenomena. Examples include being hungry or thirsty due to missed meals, physical discomfort related to lack of bathroom breaks, and feeling tense, anxious or frustrated as a consequence of being pulled in multiple directions at once.</p></section></section><section id="S18"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Adaptive work strategies</h3>
<section id="S19"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.7. Proactive work management</h4>
<p id="P31">RNs described proactive task planning in the context of shift routines and milestones, such as a goal to complete patient assessments, medications, and clinical documentation prior to first new patient admission. As a background task, RNs maintain awareness of elapsed time since last patient turns, pain medication and vitals to facilitate task clustering and proactive care delivery. Participants explained that brief activity lulls are used for rehydration, restroom breaks, or room setup for an anticipated admission.</p></section><section id="S20"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.8. Adaptive work performance</h4>
<p id="P32">RNs described similar work adjustments, undertaken to sustain essential care during demand bursts, across all focus groups (<a href="#T6" class="usa-link">Table 6</a>). RNs report that they avoid use of strategies that involve delayed, missed or reduced quality of care whenever possible. RNs provided examples of attempts to minimize patient risk during capacity strain, including choosing to delay a daily oral medication over a timed intravenous antibiotic, or to delay a dressing change rather than pain medication.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T6"><h5 class="obj_head">Table 6:</h5>
<div class="caption p"><p id="P95">Adaptive work strategies used in times of strain</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<colgroup span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
<col align="left" valign="middle" span="1">
</colgroup>
<thead><tr>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Recruit resources</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Move work in time</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Shed tasks</th>
<th align="center" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Perform tasks less thoroughly</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody><tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L11" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P96">Ask for help</p></li>
<li><p id="P97">Delegate tasks</p></li>
<li><p id="P98">Skip meals, breaks</p></li>
<li><p id="P99">Work overtime</p></li>
<li><p id="P100">Notify physicians of change in patient condition</p></li>
<li><p id="P101">Activate the code blue or rapid response team</p></li>
</ul></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L12" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P102">Perform timed tasks early or late (e.g. medications)</p></li>
<li><p id="P103">Walk past a call light or ask patients to wait</p></li>
<li><p id="P104">Obtain after-the fact co-signatures for high risk medication administration</p></li>
</ul></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L13" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P105">Delay or skip tasks (e.g. turns, hygiene, ambulation)</p></li>
<li><p id="P106">Minimize clinical documentation</p></li>
<li><p id="P107">Suspend proactive offers of assistance to other RNs</p></li>
<li><p id="P108">Skip patient education</p></li>
</ul></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" rowspan="1" colspan="1"><ul id="L14" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P109">Minimize patient teaching</p></li>
<li><p id="P110">Reduce room check frequency</p></li>
<li><p id="P111">Reduce therapeutic interactions with patients, family members</p></li>
</ul></td>
</tr></tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T6/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P33">Participants in all focus groups noted that they ask other RNs for help during times of strain. Participants noted that “asking for help” requires practice and is not always easy to do under pressure. RNs explained that they sort through their list of outstanding tasks to identify one that is appropriate to “peel off” and give to someone else. The most frequently mentioned focus of task delegation was passing medications. One nurse’s description succinctly captures adaptive work strategies articulated by multiple participants (P3 sidebar).</p></section></section><section id="S21"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Organizational Factors</h3>
<section id="S22"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.9. Flexible resource structures</h4>
<p id="P34">RNs consistently described the role of the charge nurse as a flexible resource in time of need. Nurses described common conventions for enlisting help based on skill level and availability (P11 sidebar). Hospital-wide flexible resources mentioned during focus group discussions include code blue and rapid response teams and hospital security personnel.</p></section><section id="S23"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">3.10. Workplace culture</h4>
<p id="P35">Multiple participants remarked that demand bursts that create unsafe patient situations or inability to provide high-quality care result in workplace frustration. One participant noted a gap between the anticipated and lived work experience of working as an RN, stating that time-sensitive, technical tasks such as passing medications crowd out time for therapeutic interaction and whole-person care.</p>
<p id="P36">RNs described feeling “completely responsible” for assigned patients. Reluctance to ask for help was described as a common characteristic of hospital nurses. The most frequently mentioned reason was the need to demonstrate professional competence. Participants noted that while most RNs are grateful for proactive offers of help, others can be offended. Charge nurses discussed the need to get to know workplace personalities to inform their choice of strategy in offering help to others.</p>
<p id="P37">Participants mentioned that “24-hour care” is a workplace expectation, but RNs concurrently described the cultural expectation that an outgoing RN should leave patients in an orderly state and avoid passing on lengthy tasks or tasks that typically occur on a specific work shift. One participant explained that it is a point of satisfaction and pride to have “everything done” when handing off a patient. RNs reported that it is not uncommon to work past the end of a work shift to complete care tasks or clinical documentation.</p></section></section></section><section id="S24"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. Discussion</h2>
<p id="P38">Through everyday care experiences, nurses develop expertise in recognition of workplace cues that appear when a patient care unit experiences capacity strain. Workplace cues perceived to be meaningful by frontline nurses are discoverable through focus group interview. Nurses’ narrative descriptions of past experiences provides a foundation for understanding ways in which nurses adapt their work to meet the demands of changing situations.</p>
<section id="S25"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.1. RNs experience variable demand throughout a work shift</h3>
<p id="P39">Participants’ workload trajectory artifacts depict multiple shifts between workload states during a single work shift, which is consistent with previous findings that patient needs can vary considerably across short periods of time (<a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">Garcia, 2017</a>). Resolution of competition between scheduled and emergent care tasks creates an interruptive work environment. Similar to previous findings, RN in this study described pausing current tasks to attend to a new time-sensitive care needs (<a href="#R34" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R34">Reed et al., 2018</a>). Frequent inclusion of the descriptors “yesterday” or “last week” in RN narratives suggests that RNs recently experienced capacity strain in their primary workplace.</p></section><section id="S26"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.2. Adaptive work performance enables RNs to buffer the impact of demand bursts</h3>
<p id="P40">In this study, RNs describe the use of adaptive work strategies to maintain patient care during time periods when care needs outpaced time available to address those needs. Adaptive strategies described by RNs included actions that may not be consistent with established policies and procedures. Examples include administering medications later than scheduled or obtaining an after-the-fact co-signature. Similar observations have been noted by others in multiple domains, as employers often rely on frontline workers to resolve discrepancies between organizational policy and demands encountered in practice (<a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">Rankin, 2013</a>). Nurse provided examples are consistent with previous descriptions of differences between work as imagined by hospital leaders verses work as done by frontline staff (<a href="#R38" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R38">Wears, 2015</a>), and trade-off decisions that are made by staff when it may be impossible to be both thorough and efficient (<a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">Hollnagel, 2009</a>).</p>
<p id="P41">Woods and Branlat borrow an analogy from the field of materials science (<a href="#R40" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R40">Woods and Wreathall, 2008</a>) to illustrate adaptation to increasing levels of capacity strain. Employees routinely adapt their work in small ways to account for expected variability within a work system’s competence envelope of designed-for conditions (<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">Hollnagel and Woods, 2006</a>). Although work system failure can occur at any time, the probability of failure increases as growing demand moves a work system from designed-for conditions into an area of compensation; which can escalate to an area of decompensation when adaptive capacity buffers are exhausted (<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">Cook, 2005</a>, <a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">Hollnagel et al., 2006</a>, <a href="#R31" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R31">Patterson and Wears, 2015</a>).</p>
<p id="P42">Adaptive work strategies described in this study can be mapped to strategies frequently used to navigate workplace bottlenecks: recruit resources, move work in time, shed tasks, perform tasks less thoroughly (Woods, D. personal communication, Nov 15, 2017). Similar to previous descriptions of cognitive stacking and prioritization (<a href="#R30" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R30">Patterson et al., 2011</a>) participants described maintenance of a mental list of outstanding care tasks. Dynamic re-ordering of this list enables RNs to attend to urgent needs first and address multiple care needs with each visit to a patient’s room. Addressing multiple needs in a single visit to a patient’s room, or task clustering, has been previously identified as a coping strategy to combat fatigue (<a href="#R36" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R36">Steege and Dykstra, 2016</a>) during times of capacity strain.</p>
<p id="P43">Work adjustments unlikely to result in immediate patient injury become targets for task shedding, an adaptive strategy described in previous literature (<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">Batt and Terwiesch, 2017</a>). Nurses employ clinical judgment to adapt work in ways that are least impactful to patients. For example, RNs will address abnormal vital signs over a request for a PRN medication or postpone a daily medication over an intravenous antibiotic. RN descriptions of adaptive work contain overlap with previous reports of missed nursing care (<a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">Kalisch et al., 2011</a>). Overlapping examples include reduced time talking with and educating patients, developing or updating nursing care plans (<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">Ball et al., 2014</a>, <a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">Carthon et al., 2015</a>), missed oral hygiene, skin care, delayed medications and reduced patient surveillance (<a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">Cho, 2016</a>). Similar to findings from a study of caregiver coping strategies (<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">Astvik and Melin, 2013</a>), RNs frequently skip meals and breaks during times of strain.</p>
<p id="P44">RNs perceive clinical documentation as a deferrable activity. During high demand, RNs may wait to document care delivery until a lull in activity or the end of a work shift. This adaptive strategy echoes findings from previous focus group interviews in which frontline describe clinical documentation as a “bottom of the stack” activity (Emily Patterson, personal communication, Nov 13, 2017). In addition to task delay, an inability to “sit down to chart” also connotes risk of RN dehydration and fatigue, as documentation time doubles as an opportunity to rehydrate and take a break from standing. RNs create additional time for task completion by working overtime, which is consistent with a previous finding that nurses start work early or leave later than scheduled on a majority of shifts worked (<a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">Institute of Medicine et al., 2004</a>).</p></section><section id="S27"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.3. Perceptible workplace changes emerge during times of strain</h3>
<p id="P45">Operational factors such as patient turnover, numbers of patients in isolation and other operational variables are known to influence nursing workload (<a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">Duffield et al., 2011</a>). In this study, RNs describe additional perceptible workplace cues that signify that a work system may be experiencing capacity strain. Workplace changes perceived to be meaningful cues by frontline nurses include changes in physical movement, volume of activity, and timeliness of response. Some of these changes could plausibly be detected through analysis of data naturally produced in the workplace, and potentially augment near-real-time awareness of capacity strain as it emerges in the workplace.</p>
<p id="P46">In focus group discussion, the scenarios nurses shared to provide examples of capacity strain most often involved descriptions of competing time-sensitive tasks, rather than life-threatening emergencies. Flexible structures such as rapid response and code blue teams exist for clinical emergencies, but responses to bursts in logistical demand are less formalized. Situation-level workload, defined as in-the-moment circumstances and performance obstacles encountered in the workplace (<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">Carayon and Gurses, 2005</a>) is an important factor in healthcare delivery and RN work experience. Both nurses and patients may benefit from structures that accommodate rapid and flexible allocation of resources in response to demand bursts that are not related to a clinical emergency.</p></section><section id="S28"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.4. Focused demand bursts of short duration can produce wider and more prolonged workflow impacts</h3>
<p id="P47">Demand bursts can have a ripple effect across an entire patient care unit. When an RN is occupied, other assigned patients must wait or rely on other caregivers to address emergent care needs. Cross-assignment assistance can introduce time delays for patients assigned to the nurses who stop their own work to help coworkers experiencing capacity strain. Assistance provided to bedside nurses by the charge nurse may delay completion of unit administrative care tasks or preclude charge nurse attendance at hospital-wide staffing huddles. These interlinked events are an examples of the dynamic interaction between interdependent parts of a complex system that can lead to escalation of a situation from routine to non-routine to an exceptional state (<a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">Hollnagel and Woods, 2006</a>, <a href="#R32" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R32">Perrow, 2011</a>).</p>
<p id="P48">Nurses also described extended effects of demand bursts, including a recovery period that may be longer than the initial demand burst, and “scrambling” to catch up for the rest of the rest of the shift. Additional research is needed to support work redesign and to facilitate earlier, automated recognition of small changes in a work environment so that intervention can occur before minor disturbances escalates into negative experiences and outcomes.</p></section><section id="S29"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.5. Workplace culture may influence choice of adaptive work strategy</h3>
<p id="P49">Requests for assistance with medications or other care tasks may be a relatively late sign of strain, as participants acknowledged a cultural reluctance to ask for help until an RN’s capacity is exhausted. The perception of complete responsibility for meeting all patient needs and the desire to maintain a reputation for “being able to carry my load” is consistent with past descriptions of a “supernurse” culture in which RNs perceive that they should be invulnerable to fatigue, and deliver excellent patient care through individual effort (<a href="#R37" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R37">Steege and Rainbow, 2017</a>).</p></section><section id="S30"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.6. Implications</h3>
<p id="P50">High reliability organizations recognize that early indicators of performance threats typically appear as small changes in operations (<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">Chassin and Loeb, 2013</a>). The complexity of nurse work systems requires a professional management approach that acknowledges RNs as knowledge workers who employ clinical judgement to guide their work and provide quality care (<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">American Nurses and American Nurses, 2005</a>). However, expectations that nurses will use professional judgement in making moment-to-moment decisions regarding care execution, and similar expectations that charge nurses will employ professional judgement in responding to changing situations does not preclude the potential usefulness of dynamic, data-driven monitoring to augment human surveillance of the emergence of capacity strain in hospital work systems.</p>
<p id="P51">Dynamic monitoring and early warning of changing conditions enables organizations to remain within boundaries of safe performance (<a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">Cook, 2005</a>, <a href="#R33" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R33">Rankin, 2013</a>). Yet in the hospital setting, dynamic monitoring currently focuses on changes in patients’ physiological condition. Hospitals have limited ability to dynamically detect signs of strain as a proxy indicator of elevated workload or RN overload. As a complement to patient acuity systems used to inform staffing decisions, future workload monitoring systems may be enhanced through definition of new metrics and algorithms to detect signs of adaptation in the workplace.</p>
<p id="P52">Clinical and operational data streams may contain meaningful signals of work system health and compromise. Findings from this study offer important guidance to ergonomics research and applications within nursing work systems. Specifically, this study provides a foundation for future research focused on identification of “digital echoes” of signs of capacity strain in hospital data. Real-time indicators have potential to “provide information about what is happening in intermediate stages of a process before outcomes change significantly, so that management can take actions to forestall adverse outcomes” (<a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">Hollnagel, 2010</a>). Future dynamic workplace monitoring has potential to improve both patient care delivery and clinician work experience.</p></section><section id="S31"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.7. Limitations</h3>
<p id="P53">Limitations of this study include data collection from RNs employed on two patient care units at a single academic medical center which may limit generalizability of findings to other units, facilities and care delivery models. Focus group participation was scoped to the role of RN, but future studies will benefit from inclusion of providers, nursing assistants, and other clinicians who deliver services on patient care units. As is true for any recall methodology, discussion of past workplace events carries potential for participant recall bias.</p></section></section><section id="S32"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5. Conclusions</h2>
<p id="P54">Aggregate patient demand can change across short periods of time, leading to workload fluctuations within a single patient care shift. Perceptible changes in the work environment emerge during times of capacity strain at the bedside. RNs adjust their work to meet situational demand through trade-off decisions and adaptive work performance. Knowledge contributed by RNs in this study provides a clinical foundation for future identification of temporal markers of uneven supply and demand which may facilitate future dynamic workplace monitoring and proactive management of changing workplace conditions. Additional research is needed to assess the feasibility of automated sensing of RN use of adaptive work strategies as an early sign of capacity strain at the hospital bedside.</p></section><section id="floats-group1" class="floats-group"><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX1"><h2 class="obj_head">Highlights:</h2>
<ul id="L2" class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p id="P112">Under time pressure, RNs employ adaptive work strategies to sustain care delivery</p></li>
<li><p id="P113">Nurses attend to observable workplace cues to maintain awareness of the presence or absence of capacity strain in the hospital setting</p></li>
<li><p id="P114">Nurses’ knowledge of perceptible signs of strain provides a foundation for future exploration and development of real-time indicators of capacity strain in hospital-based work systems</p></li>
</ul></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX2"><p id="P115">Participant (P)9:“The morning is usually a very busy time, because each of us has 4 patients that need something right off the bat. There’s usually new orders coming in right at 6 or 7 am; all the meds are due, somebody needs something. And right when you’re about to leave a patient room, something else happens. And you never know that’s when the ostomy’s going to burst or the dressing’s going to fall off and you’re gonna need to re-do the whole thing… You’re just hoping that some of that doesn’t happen in the morning when you have this long list of stuff to do.”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX3"><p id="P116">P12: “Sometimes I’m having a great day, and all of a sudden it gets busy for 20 minutes, so I procrastinate those meds for 45 minutes.”</p>
<p id="P117">P8: “So you need to get next door to see if that really is v-tach, or if your patient is just scratching themselves. And you look outside, cuz you’re with somebody on the commode and there’s nobody there. So you quick take off your gloves and wash your hands, run next door to check the patient, silence the alarm, then take off your gloves and wash your hands really quick to get back to make sure they haven’t gotten off the commode. Those are the times that patients can fall, and you have two patients at risk. What do you do?”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX4"><p id="P118">P15: “I got to eat lunch, yeah, just 30 minutes”. P19: “Got to go to the bathroom when I needed to.” P15: “Yeah.” P18: “Charting in real time” (laughs) P15: “Oh, that’s a dream!” P18: “It’s wishful thinking, but if you DID, then you would know that is the best day ever (laughs).”</p>
<p id="P119">P19: “Appropriate answer.”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX5"><p id="P120">P14: “There are times when I stick my head out the door, look left, look right, look at the charge desk and there’s no one in sight. And then I start calling people, and I keep getting ‘Well, we just got an admission’ or ‘they’re on a call’ and that’s when you kinda go, ‘OK, what is the highest priority here?’ And you know, something that could be potentially life threatening immediately, vs something that needs to get done, and you have to really start sorting out and prioritizing.”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX6"><p id="P121">P2: “If that list gets too long and I’m going to have to make someone wait 20 minutes for pain meds… I’ll start to delegate out important things to the charge nurse, or if I know another nurse isn’t busy, I’ll call them.</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX7"><p id="P122">P3: “When I’m really stretched I will stop offering help to other people. I will stop trying to build rapport with my patients. I will just do the essential things. I will either defer or decrease explaining what I’m doing to family… I will defer assessments on the patient who is not as sick, so it might be an hour late. I will defer clean-ups unfortunately, or they may be late. If someone is having a blood pressure crisis, the other patient might have to wait for a while. And it feels bad, but that is just what has to happen. Meds may be late. Charting will definitely be late. I will generally skip a hand-off note, breaks, bathroom time for me, and turning and mobilizing my patients. And then activities that stay the same would be essential patient care. So like I’m probably not going to clean their foley as much. I’m going to do what I have to do to keep them alive.”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX8"><p id="P123">P11: “We have a way of asking… the first person you ask is the certified nursing assistant if it’s a toilet thing. Second, you ask the other CNA. If the other CNA is not available, you ask the [patient’s assigned] nurse, and if they’re both not available, you ask the charge nurse.”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX9"><p id="P124">P3: “Sometimes there’s the worry of ‘Am I the person who’s sucking up the resources on the unit?’ I don’t want to be the person cuz then you’re like, ‘Well, are they thinking I can’t handle my assignment?’… I think nursing attracts people with personalities that are a lot of times Type A, or like gung ho, or like yeah, yeah, yeah. We just keep saying yes, I can do that, I can do that, I can do that. And then it’s like, (whispers) ‘No, you can’t.’”</p></section><section class="bt xbox font-sm" id="BX10"><p id="P125">P4: “I try to package it for [the incoming RN], like “I have these 4 items for you to do. I’m sorry to leave you with that, but that’s how the day rolled.” People tend to be agreeable with that, and vice versa. They sound apologetic in the morning ‘Oh no, can you please put in this IV or whatever’ and you’re like ‘Yeah, clearly you were doing stuff in the last 4 hours, like it’s fine’</p></section></section><section id="S33" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgements:</h2>
<p id="P55">The authors would like to acknowledge Mina Mishra for note taking assistance during focus group sessions.</p>
